TradeRefer Dashboard Redesign

Build a complete dashboard redesign for TradeRefer using shadcn/ui, Tailwind CSS, and a clean light theme.

This is a from-scratch redesign concept. Do not follow the current dashboard template. Keep the best parts of the product, but redesign the information architecture, flow, and UI so the experience is simpler, clearer, calmer, and more premium on desktop and mobile.

Overall direction:
- Light theme only
- Minimal, premium, professional, trustworthy
- Simple is better than flashy
- Strong hierarchy and spacing
- Fast scanning, low cognitive load
- Mobile-first behavior with excellent desktop layouts
- Preserve the major features that make the app strong

Core product strengths to preserve:
- Verified lead flow for businesses
- Referral network management for businesses
- Referrer discovery and applications
- Messaging between businesses and referrers
- Automated rewards and wallet visibility
- Deals and campaigns for growth
- Dual-role product model: business dashboard and referrer dashboard

Primary UX goal:
Make each dashboard feel action-oriented instead of page-oriented.
Every screen should answer:
- What needs attention now?
- What changed since last visit?
- What should I do next?

Design system requirements:
- Use shadcn/ui components and styling patterns
- Use a light neutral palette with orange as the primary accent
- White surfaces, soft borders, zinc/slate neutrals, subtle shadows
- Avoid dark heavy backgrounds except for rare highlight cards if needed
- Use a strong, readable type scale with clean section hierarchy
- Consistent button system: primary, secondary, ghost, destructive
- Consistent card system
- Consistent empty states, loading states, and error states
- Use skeleton loaders instead of excessive spinners
- Keep components reusable and clean

Recommended color feel:
- Background: very light neutral
- Surface: white
- Border: soft gray
- Text primary: dark neutral
- Text secondary: medium neutral
- Accent: orange
- Success: green
- Warning: amber
- Danger: red

Main shell and navigation:
Desktop:
- Left sidebar for primary navigation
- Top utility bar only for workspace switcher, wallet, notifications, user menu
- No second global horizontal nav under the header
- Contextual tabs only inside a page section
- Large content area with generous whitespace

Mobile:
- Bottom navigation for core destinations
- Top bar with page title and overflow actions
- Use segmented controls or tabs only inside a section when needed
- No stacked sticky nav layers
- Keep primary actions thumb-friendly

Business dashboard information architecture:
- Home
- Leads
- Network
- Inbox
- Growth
- Analytics
- Profile
- Settings

Business page model:
1. Home
Purpose:
- Central command center with priorities and recent activity
Content:
- Urgent action cards: applications to review, new leads, pending rewards, unread messages
- KPI strip: new leads, active referrers, conversion rate, reward spend, attributed revenue
- Recent activity feed
- Quick actions: review applications, invite referrers, create deal, update program settings
- Performance snapshot by week/month toggle
Desktop layout:
- Top summary row
- Left main activity column
- Right action sidebar
Mobile layout:
- Stacked cards
- Action tray near the top
- Feed and metrics below

2. Leads
Purpose:
- Review, unlock, track, and update lead outcomes
Desktop layout:
- Master-detail interface
- Left list of leads with filters and search
- Right detail pane with lead info and actions
- Sticky action footer inside detail pane if needed
Mobile layout:
- Lead list first
- Tapping opens full-screen detail view
- Sticky bottom action bar: unlock, call, message, mark outcome
Key UX improvements:
- Reduce status complexity into plain language states
- Make next step obvious for each lead
- Show confidence/trust markers clearly

3. Network
This is a single workspace with internal tabs:
- Active Referrers
- Applications
- Program Settings
Purpose:
- Businesses manage the full referral network in one place
Desktop:
- Page header and summary stats
- Tabs below the page header
- Each tab uses purpose-built content
Mobile:
- One page with segmented control at top
- Clean stacked cards
Active Referrers tab:
- Search
- Referrer cards or rows
- Performance stats
- Custom fee edit action
- Quick message action
Applications tab:
- Review queue with clear approve/reject actions
- Application card shows quality signals and notes
- Message before approval option
Program Settings tab:
- Default lead fee
- Reward milestones
- Invite link
- Program description and simple settings
Key UX rule:
- No duplicate routes for referrers, applications, and force management
- This section should feel unified and obvious

4. Inbox
Purpose:
- A real communication center, not a side feature
Desktop:
- Conversation list on left
- Active thread on right
- Filters for unread, active, archived
Mobile:
- Conversation list
- Full-screen thread view
Features:
- Search
- Unread emphasis
- Simple composer
- Shared context badges like lead, application, or referrer

5. Growth
This is one workspace with internal tabs:
- Deals
- Campaigns
Purpose:
- Separate evergreen offers from temporary growth pushes
Deals:
- Evergreen offers that referrers can share anytime
Campaigns:
- Time-based or bonus-driven pushes
Desktop:
- Header, summary, tabs, main list/grid
Mobile:
- Stacked cards and compact action buttons
Key UX improvement:
- Make the difference between Deals and Campaigns very obvious visually and in copy

6. Analytics
Purpose:
- Show the most important business performance signals only
Content:
- Lead volume trend
- Conversion funnel
- Top referrers
- Reward spend
- Revenue influenced or attributed
Keep it simple:
- Avoid too many charts
- Prefer 4 to 6 strong widgets over 15 weak ones

7. Profile
Purpose:
- Manage public storefront and trust signals
Desktop:
- Edit panel left, preview panel right
Mobile:
- Preview-first with edit sections below
Content:
- Business identity
- Categories and service areas
- Description
- Images
- Trust indicators
- Preview of public business page

8. Settings
Purpose:
- Account, notifications, payout, billing, team access if needed
Use a simple settings layout:
- Side section nav on desktop
- Stacked groups on mobile

Referrer dashboard information architecture:
- Home
- Find Businesses
- My Businesses
- Referrals
- Inbox
- Earnings
- Profile
- Settings

Referrer page model:
1. Home
Purpose:
- Show earning progress and clear next steps
Content:
- Earnings summary
- Pending actions
- Application statuses
- Recent referrals
- Suggested businesses to apply to

2. Find Businesses
Purpose:
- Discovery and applications
Desktop:
- Search and filter rail
- Business results grid/list
Mobile:
- Filter sheet and stacked cards
Make it easy to understand:
- fee
- approval chance signals if available
- location and trade fit
- quick apply

3. My Businesses
Purpose:
- View approved, pending, and paused business relationships
Desktop:
- Filtered cards or table-like rows
Mobile:
- Relationship cards with status chip and quick actions

4. Referrals
Purpose:
- Submit and track all referred leads
Desktop:
- List/detail or board-style status sections
Mobile:
- Simple list with strong status states

5. Inbox
Purpose:
- Messaging with businesses
Keep it aligned with business inbox patterns

6. Earnings
Purpose:
- Make money clarity extremely high
Content:
- Available balance
- Pending balance
- Recent payouts
- Referral earnings history
- Withdraw action
Desktop:
- Summary cards plus history table
Mobile:
- Summary cards plus stacked transaction list

7. Profile
Purpose:
- Show credibility and improve approval odds
Content:
- Bio
- Location
- Expertise/trade knowledge
- Social proof or completion score if relevant

8. Settings
Purpose:
- Account, payout method, notifications, privacy

Cross-platform interaction rules:
- No tables on mobile unless absolutely necessary
- On mobile use cards, sections, bottom sheets, drawers, and segmented controls
- Use dialogs sparingly; prefer sheets on mobile
- Keep all primary actions visible without hunting
- No more than one sticky navigation layer at a time
- Use destructive actions carefully and clearly
- Make states and transitions obvious

Component guidance using shadcn:
- Sidebar for desktop app shell
- Tabs for page-level contextual sections only
- Card for summaries and grouped content
- Sheet for mobile filters and actions
- Dialog for confirmation and focused edit flows
- Dropdown menu for overflow actions
- Table on desktop only when truly useful
- Badge for statuses
- Toast for success/error feedback
- Skeleton for loading states
- Avatar, Input, Select, Button, Separator, ScrollArea where appropriate

Visual style notes:
- Rounded corners should feel modern but restrained
- Use generous padding and white space
- Avoid overusing gradients
- One accent color at a time
- Use icons sparingly and consistently
- Make empty states calm and helpful

Page-specific content priorities:
Business Home should prioritize:
- new leads
- new applications
- unread messages
- pending confirmations

Referrer Home should prioritize:
- available balance
- pending approvals
- recent referrals
- suggested businesses

Lead statuses should be simplified into plain English, for example:
- New
- Contacted
- Qualified
- Won
- Lost
- Reward Pending

Copy style:
- Short, clear, plain English
- Avoid internal jargon where possible
- Replace confusing labels with obvious ones
- Keep button labels action-based

Accessibility and usability requirements:
- Strong contrast in light theme
- Large tap targets on mobile
- Clear focus states
- Keyboard-friendly desktop flows
- Avoid clutter and visual competition

Deliverable style:
Generate polished dashboard screens and component layouts for both desktop and mobile based on this system.
Prioritize these screens first:
- Business Home desktop and mobile
- Business Leads desktop and mobile
- Business Network desktop and mobile
- Referrer Home desktop and mobile
- Referrer Find Businesses desktop and mobile

Design these screens as if this is a premium SaaS marketplace workflow product using shadcn/ui in a light theme.

Important constraints:
- Keep the experience simple
- Keep the most valuable existing features
- Improve navigation clarity dramatically
- Improve mobile usability dramatically
- Avoid using the existing top-nav-plus-submenu dashboard pattern
- Prefer a unified workspace model with contextual sections
